1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:03,964
If you're comparing two quantitative variables to one another,

2

00:00:03,964  -->  00:00:05,929
say price and sales,

3

00:00:05,929  -->  00:00:07,929
or heights and weights,

4

00:00:07,929  -->  00:00:12,800
the most common plot for such an analysis is the scatter plot.

5

00:00:12,800  -->  00:00:14,690
These plots can be used to visualize

6

00:00:14,689  -->  00:00:20,144
both the strength and the direction of the relationship between the two variables.

7

00:00:20,144  -->  00:00:23,765
This is an example of a strong positive relationship,

8

00:00:23,765  -->  00:00:29,530
that is, as one variable increases the other variable also increases.

9

00:00:29,530  -->  00:00:33,380
While this is an example of a strong negative relationship.

10

00:00:33,380  -->  00:00:38,600
That is, as one variable increases the other variable decreases.

11

00:00:38,600  -->  00:00:41,810
As the points become more spread out from one another,

12

00:00:41,810  -->  00:00:43,969
this weakens the relationship.

13

00:00:43,969  -->  00:00:47,210
So to identify strong or weak relationships,

14

00:00:47,210  -->  00:00:51,439
we aren't so much looking at the slope associated with the relationship,

15

00:00:51,439  -->  00:00:53,234
which is changing here.

16

00:00:53,234  -->  00:00:55,039
These all have the same strength.

17

00:00:55,039  -->  00:00:59,469
But rather, the closeness of the points as we saw before.

18

00:00:59,469  -->  00:01:03,034
Generally, we consider strength as either weak,

19

00:01:03,034  -->  00:01:09,239
moderate or strong, and direction as simply positive or negative.

20

00:01:09,239  -->  00:01:11,359
A numeric value used to capture

21

00:01:11,359  -->  00:01:14,974
these two aspects is known as the correlation coefficient,

22

00:01:14,974  -->  00:01:19,549
often just denoted by a lower case r. The correlation coefficient

23

00:01:19,549  -->  00:01:24,620
is used to tell us the strength and the direction of a linear relationship.

24

00:01:24,620  -->  00:01:29,180
The correlation coefficient is always between -1 and 1,

25

00:01:29,180  -->  00:01:32,540
where the closer it is to 1 or -1,

26

00:01:32,540  -->  00:01:34,520
the stronger the relationship.

27

00:01:34,519  -->  00:01:37,979
The negative tells you that there's a negative relationship,

28

00:01:37,980  -->  00:01:41,225
while a positive tells you there's a positive relationship.

29

00:01:41,224  -->  00:01:45,099
You will get some practice with this in the quizzes that follow.
